snippet.textDisplay: We are pretty certain vis a vis black holes that you can have something that looks like infinite mass in a given location, yet still exist in a space that can contain more than just that infinite mass--by a lot. My best guess is that the Universe in a singularity before the Big Bang is just the observable Universe, and that rather than it being a single point, it's an infinite expanse of "infinitely dense" mass that was expanding before the Big Bang. The Universe reached a point of phase change and the infinite density began to separate into a larger (i.e. expanding) infinite space. (Some infinities are larger than others.) This may be similar to what physicists propose could happen far into the future called the Big Rip, which would be yet another phase change.

NO BIG BANG! It's in the dustbin of theroetical history...
We live in an Oscillating Universe, eternally expanding and contracting every trillion years or so (give or take).
A 450 billion year expansion phase, as energy is converted into matter... Then a 450 billion year contraction phase, as the process is reversed and matter is converted back into energy.
The universe will reach its maximum size, about, 312 billion light years across, about 22 times larger than it is today...
... Stop having these morons on your show (Neil de Grasse Tyson is biggest knob clown, closely followed by Brian Cox)... If you must, ask them why were now finding structures that seem pre date the big bang? (I.e. older than 14.6 billion years)
